WEBVTT

NOTE
Draft captions matching the conversational narration in demo-script.md /
demo-transcript.md. Cue times follow the script's timing budget (target 6:30).
Before acceptance, reconcile them against what is actually said on the recording;
captions never override the real narration. Synthetic MVP — no customer data.

1
00:00.000 --> 00:04.000
Synthetic MVP — no customer data.

2
00:04.000 --> 00:11.000
Real quick before anything —
everything here runs on fake data.

3
00:11.000 --> 00:17.000
It's a synthetic demo, not hooked up
to Armadin's real systems.

4
00:17.000 --> 00:25.000
A swarm attacks a customer, finds a bunch
of stuff, writes it down...

5
00:25.000 --> 00:30.000
then the engagement ends and it throws
the notebook away.

6
00:30.000 --> 00:35.000
Next quarter it starts from zero.
That's what I'm fixing — the memory.

7
00:35.000 --> 00:43.000
One command does the whole thing.
Preflight is just me being careful —

8
00:43.000 --> 00:50.000
it checks Java, Docker, the build, the
safety guards, and changes nothing.

9
00:50.000 --> 00:58.000
Then it loads Engagement 1. Every fact is
its own locked-down, tenant-scoped row.

10
00:58.000 --> 01:05.000
When it's done we draw a hard line:
everything we knew, as of right now.

11
01:05.000 --> 01:13.000
Storing stuff is fine — the real question is
does the memory change what you do next.

12
01:13.000 --> 01:21.000
There's a planner, and it runs at that
Engagement 1 line, before we know round two.

13
01:21.000 --> 01:30.000
And this is what people get wrong:
it's so easy to let the future leak in.

14
01:30.000 --> 01:38.000
So the planner only ever sees opaque IDs.
No labels, no results.

15
01:38.000 --> 01:46.000
Memory off, it goes in order: A, B, C.

16
01:46.000 --> 01:56.000
Memory on, it knows one got fixed last time
and pulls it to the front: C, A, B.

17
01:56.000 --> 02:08.000
Both plans actually run — same starting point,
same outcomes baked in.

18
02:08.000 --> 02:18.000
And the bug that came back — memory catches it
on the first move, not the third.

19
02:18.000 --> 02:25.000
Three to one. And "zero events at planning"
is me proving nothing leaked.

20
02:25.000 --> 02:34.000
Between the two engagements the pod got a new
ID, a new name, a new IP —

21
02:34.000 --> 02:43.000
everything you'd key on changed. But the
Deployment underneath is the same.

22
02:43.000 --> 02:52.000
So we keep it as the same asset, and the
finding stays stuck to it.

23
02:52.000 --> 03:02.000
Opposite case: something genuinely fuzzy,
a reused DNS name with nothing behind it.

24
03:02.000 --> 03:11.000
It doesn't guess. It marks it ambiguous and
won't let it move any numbers.

25
03:11.000 --> 03:20.000
It'd rather say "I don't know" than merge two
things that might not match.

26
03:20.000 --> 03:30.000
Same exact Engagement 2 facts —
I'm not touching the data.

27
03:30.000 --> 03:40.000
I'm just changing how much history
it's allowed to look at.

28
03:40.000 --> 03:50.000
No memory, a normal scan: three detections,
one not-detected, one partial.

29
03:50.000 --> 04:00.000
And the finding nobody retested? It just isn't
there. The scan can't even see it.

30
04:00.000 --> 04:12.000
Turn history back on, same facts,
and suddenly they mean something.

31
04:12.000 --> 04:24.000
New, still open, verified fixed, regressed,
not retested, inconclusive.

32
04:24.000 --> 04:36.000
"Verified fixed" only counts if we reran the
same check and it came back clean.

33
04:36.000 --> 04:46.000
Not seeing a bug is not the same as
the bug being gone.

34
04:46.000 --> 04:55.000
Only memory can tell you a fix came back,
or that you forgot to retest something.

35
04:55.000 --> 05:05.000
This is the unglamorous stuff
that just has to work.

36
05:05.000 --> 05:15.000
Same event twice — no-op.
A conflicting one — rejected.

37
05:15.000 --> 05:25.000
Ask for a report before the data's complete —
it blocks you.

38
05:25.000 --> 05:35.000
Shuffle the arrival order — same report.
Kill a transaction halfway — nothing left behind.

39
05:35.000 --> 05:45.000
Same facts, same answer, every time.
That's what you have to trust first.

40
05:45.000 --> 05:55.000
Why does Armadin care — this turns a one-off scan
into something you'd pay for every quarter.

41
05:55.000 --> 06:04.000
Prove a fix regressed, prove something got
verified, catch what nobody retested.

42
06:04.000 --> 06:14.000
Straight about what it isn't: not production-scale,
not wired into Armadin, no auth or privacy claims.

43
06:14.000 --> 06:25.000
The way it gets real: point a real swarm at a real
target, write one adapter to this same contract.

44
06:25.000 --> 06:35.000
That adapter's real work. But the memory engine
underneath it is the part that's done.

45
06:35.000 --> 06:46.000
Everything you saw — the 3-to-1, identity, the six
categories, the correctness checks —

46
06:46.000 --> 06:55.000
none of it is hardcoded. It's computed from
the actual run, identical every time.

47
06:55.000 --> 07:00.000
Fake data, yeah. But a real result.
Thanks for watching.
